utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: He's the media.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: When they write about him this is how they write, Greg, they say, you know, the Texas wind hit his hair as he leaned in to the food truck and ordered a burrito to give to the homeless veteran playing a broken guitar. It's like they sensationalize the most trivial things about him like he's Jesus.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: But Kennedy has the best nickname.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I want to get to Chris Matthews who basically, you know, he's no conservative saying pretty much the same thing that you're saying about this recent Vanity Fair.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: By the way, bring back that cover of -- that cover is the best kiss I've seen for a candidate in a long time. I always say the candidate wins who's got the sun in his face who looks like sunny optimistic, not the indoor bureaucrat sitting at some desk somewhere. That's the image you want.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: But it's not the sun in his face, it's the media, you know, kissing his butt. It's not about the sun.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Wait a second, he's the outsider. He's the outsider in the Trumpian style, right?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: OK.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: He's not a senator. He's not a mayor. He's not a governor.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: Yeah, Juan, let me give Kennedy a compliment. Because you've said this on Outnumbered the other day, his nickname should be Beta.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: Yeah, Beta O'Dork.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Hey, hey, she said it here on “The Five” first. She said it on “The Five.”

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: Because he does comes across as weak.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: And if he runs in the general election against President Trump who projects strength I don't think that's going to work for Beta.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: How come he got so much reaction, Lisa? So much reaction from the president? So much reaction --

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: Because of people like you, Juan.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: His action is funny. I mean, you cannot deny the hand movement. By the way, I'll got to give a hat tip to red tees for the inflatable man comparison because -- that's perfect. It's either that -- he's a cross between the inflatable man and slender man. I'm not sure what it is.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: He's not the transformational figure that Barack Obama was.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: I'm sorry.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: Barack Obama also didn't have a super crowded primary field either.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That's true.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: All he had to do was elbow Hillary out of the way.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Barack Obama wasn't a favorite.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Oh, yeah, he was.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: It's big disservice to Barack Obama to compare Beto to him.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I don't know. I think people also say John F. Kennedy. So, are you guys --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Wow, Juan, you have a big estimation of Beto.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: All right, we've got to move on. Up next, Jussie Smollett back in court today after being charged in an alleged hate crime hoax.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: A defiant Jussie Smollett back in court today facing 16 felony charges after allegedly staging a hate crime.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: So we're going to need a plea. Let me know if you want me to formally read the indictment. You can have the option to have me read it or you can waive reading. I will need a plea of guilty or not guilty.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: Your honor, we waive formal reading of the indictment, and Mr. Smollett enters a plea of not guilty.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Thank you.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Smollett pleading not guilty to those felonies. But remember, police have provided a ton of evidence showing that Smollett paid two brothers to stage the hate crime hoax. Greg, I guess one of the strategies of the defense is to say that this is prosecutorial overreach.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Pile up like 16 felonies because they're angry --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: -- because he made them work -- they've made them work so hard for two weeks.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: So what it does is it's puts them in a weird spot because when you're saying prosecutorial overreach you're not saying not guilty.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You're saying -- you're saying, hey, you did something bad but it wasn't that bad.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: So you've already kind of given away --you know, let this thing play out and he gets due process, which is important. He might be innocent. My feeling is the media is not going to learn anything. Every time you dangle a story in front of the media that matches their assumptions they keep going there. They keep burning their hand on that stove so many times. It's like none. So they don't feel any ouch anymore. It's just completely numb. Here's the thing --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: They're like Kavanaugh.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Here's a prediction. I think that judging by his behavior he might do something really sleazy, which is he's going to pin the blame on the two guys that he hired and he probably promised those guys, you know, money -- not just money but his own celebrity friendship and promises of more work. And then I think just to save his ass he's going to throw it all on them.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And he's back at Empire.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: Yeah. And the producers have said, you know, we're going to let justice play out. We want due process, which is fine.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: If that's one of the rules that we have then we apply to many sides. I don't have a problem with that at all. And they can wait to see if he is, in fact, found guilty in a court of law.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: But the cast isn't very happy with him.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: I think, sometimes, big media companies act too quickly, too hastily, they're reacting to the online mob.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: And this is a good case where it's pretty clear that something is amiss here. There's so many facts we've heard so far in this story that don't bode well for Mr. Smollett. But, you know, in the end they may say we don't want to turf the show. He can learn from this. His character is critical to the entire franchise. Therefore, we're going to keep him on board.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And also the defense saying, Juan, they want cameras in the courtroom.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: This was very interesting to me.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I thought so, too.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Because what the lawyer said was we want everyone to see the false evidence that's been pushed upon us, and the fact that our presumption of innocence has been taken away from us in the United States. I'm like, wow. So you think there's something there that can get the court of public opinion back on your side.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: I think they're just trying to raise his profile, Juan.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: Yeah, exactly.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Raise his profile? You mean -- when he goes --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It can't hurt. I don't think it can hurt him at all.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: I am so sick and tired of talking about Jussie Smollett because we're giving him exactly what he wants. All he wants -- he's a D-list actor nobody ever heard of him before this happened. All he does is wants attention. He's allegedly upset because a letter he sent himself, or allegedly sent himself, did not get enough attention which is why he allegedly staged this attack. That's why he wants cameras in the courtroom --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: He wants cameras to help raise his profile even more so then he can parlay it into something else after this?

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: Yeah. He didn't have to show up today, and choose to show up because he wants the attention. Also, he did that Good Morning America interview. He wanted to do the interview to get an additional 15 minutes of fame. So that's what this is all about in my opinion. I just think he wants attention. He wants infamy and we're giving it to them. I'm tired of talking about it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So here's the other side, Lisa. Somebody --

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: There's another side?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Somebody who committed such an atrocious crime, if it's true, how does that help him? I just think that it damages his reputation --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- people who will be his fans.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Think about O.J. Simpson which is far worse, obviously. So I'm not comparing. But that -- the cameras helped him, I believe.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yeah, yeah. But that's -- so, OK. Let's say it goes to a trial. I thought O.J. was guilty. I think probably this guy. But, guess what, the jury didn't agree with me, right? So even if the jury doesn't agree, I notice that the people on the set of Empire, you were talking about this moment ago, Jesse. They don't like what's going on.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: No.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: He's been pushed off at the last two segments of this season's show, like done.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: Yeah. No, he was written off and then the season premier is coming up. And, you know --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And, Kennedy, how will the media play this? If he is convicted here, we're definitely not going to see the same attention as we saw when he first made the allegation. You can almost slowly see this fading out of the media.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: And I don't think it's going to go that far. I don't think it's going to get --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Do you think they're going to cut a deal?

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: -- full jury trial. Absolutely. And they're going to -- to keep him out of prison because it's going to be really expensive. If he goes through the entire process --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Do you say he stays out of prison? Do you say he's stays out of prison?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: By the way, I don't think he has a whole lot of prison time on the charges. The charges are rather small --

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: There's just so many of them.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: There's so many. But I don't think -- I don't think it's going to prison. I think it's guilt. And I think it would damage him and his status as an actor for all time. He would always be seen as that guy.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Prison, no prison?

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: I hope so. I also think -- if you're the police how mad are you the fact that this guy is so dumb he writes a check to the two people allegedly part of it. And you're like, you're wasting my time, people are out on the streets getting murdered.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: That was so funny.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I think the thing that gets me is the celebrity support. You can't hold people accountable for being stupid, but I kind of want to. I mean, I really -- all the people that were lighting the torches, they weren't given any due process. I want him to get due process. And I'm willing to be -- I'm willing to be surprise.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: And people --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: More about Ellen Page than anybody.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: -- without any skepticism at all with whoever. And I hope from this -- and Covington and Kavanaugh, first of all, all of those people should be on Celebrity Big Brother.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: Brett Kavanaugh and Nick Sandmann, they should all should be on Celebrity Big Brother.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right, is California letting killers off easy after the state's liberal governor puts pause on the death penalty? Details ahead.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: California kicking off a huge debate about the death penalty. Governor Gavin Newsom signing an executive order putting a moratorium on executions of 737 inmates now on death row. Here's Governor Newsom.

utterances.speaker: GOV. GAVIN NEWSOM, D-CALIF.
utterances.utterance: I cannot sign off on executing hundreds and hundreds of human beings knowing, knowing that among them would be innocent human beings. I believe the death penalty is wrong. And I'm exercising my right pursuing to the voters, the will of voters, and the constitution to do that right.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: The governor also calling the death penalty, and here I'm quoting, ineffective, irreversible and immoral. President Trump blasting the move saying, quote, friends and families of the always forgotten victims are not thrilled neither am I. So in the break, Kennedy and Greg, I guess you're both Californians, so how do you guys feel? You decide who goes first here.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well, I believe that the death penalty is the ultimate crime prevention because that person can't commit another crime. However, I would support this if they have an alternative, right? If there was an alternative to the death penalty and it's not life imprisonment because human beings adapt to everything. For example, I could adapt to prison because I like order and discipline.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You would not.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, I would. The point is --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: The point is you're still a conscious, living human being in prison. And in five years you're going to be wearing that like a comfy sweater. I don't know what there is as punishment that could make the families -- and then you have the families that have to worry about paroles. I know these are death sentences. But, I mean, like, we never know what happens when somebody gets freed because of -- oh, we found out this.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: OK. But I think you are a person who would generally oppose the idea of government --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- using its power to impose death.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So --

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: And that's where I tend to rest. And this is one of those issues where I've struggled with it for a long time because the sense of vengeance in me, especially for some of the people in California who are on death row for committing atrocious, horrible, unthinkable acts against people, the vengeful side of me, the one who really seeks justice wants to see these people put to death and have their lives ended as they ended the lives of other innocent people. However, I don't think it's the role of the state to do that. I don't think the state has the authority to take people's lives. And he's right and -- you know, I don't necessarily agree with him about all the touchy feely stuff. But he is right if there are innocent people, it's not worth taking the risk of killing someone who has not commit the crime -- committed the crime.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So, Jesse, we know now that 20 states have abolished the death penalty, four states including California have a moratorium in place. I will point out the critics say that in California there was a vote by the voters to keep the death penalty.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: On the other hand, they elected someone who is an expressed opponent of the death penalty in Gavin Newsom.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: So there was a referendum and voters in California not only wanted to keep it, they wanted to speed up executions. So by thwarting the will of the people there that's a big affront towards the Democratic --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But they've elected him.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: They elected him but not on that single issue, Juan. On that single issue, the people of California, a liberal state, want people on death row executed faster than they are now. Because, right now, families, victim's families are -- through their tax money paying for these people to eat and to keep, and they like to see justice done because they invite the families to the execution, and mentally that is a big part of closure and healing process. Now, he's only doing this because he's running for president in 2024. And he wants to protect his left flank against criticism in case he executes a guy where DNA gets him off later and he's exonerated. So -- but you can't be a commander-in-chief if you think I'm not going to kill a thousand terrorists because one of them might be innocent. If you a lob a missile into a terrorist training camp, you can't worry about civilian casualties, and I think that's where he's wrong. Look at some of the people on death row, Juan. Scott Peterson killed his wife and his son. The grim sleeper murdered nine women and a teenager. And then Charles Ng murdered 11 people. I mean, I can go on and on --

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: And 26 people on death row in California have taken their own lives because of the process. I mean, to the point of proposition 66 which is what voters passed in California. The process takes so long and it's so incredibly expensive -- And then voters didn't just vote in 2016, they actually upheld capital punishment in the State of California 11 times since 1972. But I do find it a little bit ironic that Gavin Newsom immediately took part in assisted suicide of his mother in 2002 when it was actually a felony in the state at the time of California. So I find it a little bit ironic that now he is trying to defend --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, let me come back --

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: -- these people on death row.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well, I mean there is a weirdness where and you can go both sides in this that the people that are generally against the death penalty are also pro-abortion.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: And that's it. And then you could go the other side. The better argument against death penalty. And I don't - perhaps people are making this is that if you examine the brain chemistry of people, they change. So, if you're an 18-year-old or 20-year-old and you do something absolutely heinous, what do you like, but you're not the same person. If you're going to pursue this argument, you've got to pursue it with science. Is that the same person?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: All right, so Lisa I just want to do the politics for a second, because the politics say that this issue breaks down along partisan lines. 77 percent of Republicans, yes to the death penalty; 65 percent of Democrats, no. The people most likely to support the death penalty, older white males. Heavy on this issue. And then it comes to what Greg was talking about, the same group would say, hey, abortion, we're not killing babies, don't do that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Because babies are innocent.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But we're going to kill people.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: Well, I think for Gavin Newsom this issue might play well in a state like well actually not even, because as we pointed out in California, voters have upheld this, 11 times since 1972. I don't think it's a good political issue. I don't think it necessarily protects his flank from the left. I don't think it's a good political issue for Gavin Newsom particularly if he wants to run in 2020, 2024 rather. And I think President Trump running as a law enforcement candidate, law and order candidate does help him. I think it helped him in 2016. I think it'll help him against in 2020 particularly depending on who the Democrat is and if they seem weak on these issues. I also think that's why in the 2018 election, even on the issue of immigration, you had Democrats like the Center for American Progress sending out memos to candidates even in swing districts saying don't touch the issue of sanctuary cities. This is bad for you politically saying that it packs a punch. So, I think that's why President Trump's positioning for 2020 and I think it's going to help him.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, I think Kamala Harris, the Senator from California came out in support of Newsom and she is running for President.

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: And she was for the death penalty when she was Attorney General.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Correct.

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: So, she's a big hypocrite on this issue.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, but she changed obviously.

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: How convenient for her.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Shocking new developments in that college admissions scandal including a 500, I'm right on this billion.

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: Billion.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes, billion-dollar lawsuit. That's next, right here on “The Five.”

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: With you. College, shocking new developments in the fallout over the massive college admission scandal. Actress Lori Loughlin's daughter was reportedly spending spring break on a USC officials' yacht, while her mom was being charged in court and big lawsuits are now flying. And again, it's just the beginning, including one from a Stanford student and others suing these colleges, all named in the cheating scam. A mother and son are also suing 45 defendants in the alleged scam for a whopping $500 billion. How about that number. Elizabeth Warren apparently forgot to look in the mirror after her own college controversy. Liz. So, as a parent how much sympathy would you have for these parents who are embroiled in this alleged cheating scandal.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: Zero.

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: So, Jesse, is that how much sympathy she has or the chance she has in becoming our next President.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: As a fake Indian, how much sympathy do you have. No, I mean she really stepped in it there and the irony was lost. You know these people are so not self-aware. I think the best place to find out bad news is a yacht, really softens the walk.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: International waters especially. Another title.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Another. I am going to write that. You know if I get wind that Fox is going to fire me, I'm going to say this, guys, can you give me 24 hours. I'm going to get on a yacht. And then that it's going to soften the blow. I also like--

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: As long as they can contact you, you're still going to avoid.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I want to know in a very comfortable--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Rules don't apply out there.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's true. I also like the fact that it was on a trustee's yacht. I like the term trustee. It's something I aspire to, it combines the air of an ivory tower with the weight of a gold bar. You'd like that one, Greg?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: But I have a solution here. I don't want prison time for these people. I just want them to start a scholarship fund for people at USC that are qualified and then that's what they could do. And then for the girl--

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: No.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I don't want her in trouble either, because she has already been humiliated.

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: No one at USC needs anything, because they're a bunch of cheating, lying losers. It is maybe the flimsiest college in the land, is it not Greg?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I agree completely as a Berkeley graduate. OK. I've said it before, but college has become too much of a virtue signal. That's why everybody keeps getting higher and higher degrees. Now, it's easy to regret not having any military service for me to say that because it entails no risk on my part. I'm too old, but I submit that military service is a higher status symbol and a higher cooler virtue signal than going to college. And I think that if corporations had made it so that you get into the front of the hiring line as opposed to Harvard or Stanford by going and being in the military that would have - it would have such a greater impact and you get more experience. You learn so many things about structure and discipline in the military. Again, I'm saying this is not when you add it and wishes I did.

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: Stolen valor, little.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. Stolen valor right now. Well, back in Nam. It was four.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You're right, because if you run for office in this country it's much better if you've served overseas and if you went to an Ivy League university.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: You know what, I'm going to break this down with Lisa Boothe, because she's going to understand what I'm laying down here.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: I hope so.

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: Immediately.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: Not like this.

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: You will get this completely. So, for some reason, we've placed a four-year degree on this pedestal.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: That is, you know you talk about flimsy. It is unsustainable the amount of debt that we've got in this country. The amount of college debt and young people can't get married, they can't buy houses because they're saddled with it and it creates an economic immobility. What we need are plumbers and contractors and welders. If the welder's consortium was a little bit smarter and they had an Instagram account with hot welders. Don't you think that by creating shirtless welding Instagram stars, they would bring more young and women into the welding fold.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: Well, when you put it that way. Yes, obviously.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Welding.

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
